<validation>
1. Setup controlled DNS server with rebinding capability
2. Demonstrate initial connection to attacker IP (203.0.113.1)
3. Show DNS resolution change to target IP (127.0.0.1 or internal)
4. Prove browser makes request to target thinking same-origin
5. Capture internal response and exfiltrate to attacker
6. Test with multiple browsers to show consistency
7. Demonstrate impact: credential theft, internal data access, or service control
</validation>

<false_positives>
- DNS changes that don't result in browser requests
- Blocked by browser security features (CORB, CORP)
- Internal services with strong authentication
- DNS pinning preventing rebinding
- Network firewalls blocking internal access
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Cloud credential theft (AWS/GCP/Azure metadata)
- Internal network reconnaissance and exploitation
- Router/IoT device compromise
- Private data exfiltration from localhost services
- Corporate intranet access
- Bypass of network-based access controls
- Cross-site request forgery on internal services
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. TTL=0 or TTL=1 for rapid rebinding—test browser caching behavior
2. Use multiple A records for race condition approach (simpler setup)
3. WebSocket provides persistent exfil channel during rebinding
4. Target 169.254.169.254 first (cloud metadata)—high impact, common target
5. Test localhost ports: 8080, 9200, 6379, 2375, 5000 for common services
6. Collect auth tokens before rebind, replay after to target
7. Use iframes to isolate rebinding from main page
8. Monitor DNS queries to confirm rebinding occurred
9. Some browsers block localhost/RFC1918 in mixed content—use HTTP everywhere
10. Test on cloud VMs—most vulnerable to metadata attacks
11. Combine with CSRF payloads for admin actions on internal services
12. Use wildcard DNS for flexible target configuration per victim
</pro_tips>

<remember>DNS rebinding bypasses Same-Origin Policy by making internal resources appear same-origin. Defend with DNS pinning, Host header validation, authentication on internal services, and blocking external DNS resolution to internal IPs. Always require authentication on services listening on localhost or internal networks.</remember>
</dns_rebinding_guide>
